,"display_name":"Col. Edward Newman Packard Jr."},"birth":{"year":1883,"month":5,"day":14,"city":"Dorchester","county":"Suffolk County","state":"Massachusetts","country":"United States"},"baptism":{},"death":{"year":1968,"month":11,"day":16,"city":"Pensacola","county":"Escambia County","state":"Florida","country":"United States"},"residence":{},"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM384","plot_notes":"FindAGrave #139501351. Pine Ridge Cemetery Saranac Lake NY."},"classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_paths_to_thomas":0,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"is_progenitor":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"parents":{"father_id":"X02828","father_research_notes":"Father: Rev. Edward Newman Packard D.D. (b.c.1840s, New England minister). Family lived in Evanston IL c.1872-1876, then Dorchester MA. Siblings: Charlotte Mellen Packard (b.1872, d.1954); Elizabeth Ford Packard Quereau (b.1876, d.1948), whose son Edmund Packard Quereau lived to 98; Agnes Kent Packard Cooper (b.1881, d.1963), who served as president of New York Women's Board of Missions 1921-22 and was a twenty-year member of American Board of Commissioners for Foreign Missions. Agnes's son Lawrence Carleton Cooper (Michigan Phi Beta Kappa MBA 1932) was a Bankers Trust VP for utility investments. Lawrence's daughter Carol Packard Cooper (b.1941, d.2016) was one of the country's first open heart surgery patients, operated on by Dr. Denton Cooley in 1959 aged 17. Agnes's husband Dr. Hermon Charles Cooper earned a chemistry PhD at Heidelberg 1900 and co-authored an inorganic chemistry textbook with Dutch chemist Arnold Holleman in 1901; he was also a research associate at MIT."},"number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"HD4419","date_year":1919,"location_country":"United States","children_ids":["HD4421","HD4422","HD4423"]}],"education":[],"career":[],"military_service":[{"war":"World War I","rank":"Unknown","notes":"Served two years during WWI. Specific rank not documented."},{"war":"World War II","war_id":"WAR008","rank":"Colonel","rank_start":"Lieutenant Colonel","rank_end":"Colonel","rank_year_start":1941,"rank_year_end":1946,"unit":"Fort Dix and Holloran General Hospitals","notes":"Medical chief of Fort Dix and Holloran General Hospitals, combined 6,500 beds. Received Legion of Merit for service."}],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"artworks":[],"tags":["wwi","wwii","army","physician"],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"military","header":"Commanded 6,500-bed WWII hospitals; received Legion of Merit","body":"Edward Packard served as a physician in WWI and then from 1941 to 1946 as lieutenant colonel and then colonel commanding 6,500 combined beds at Fort Dix and Holloran General Hospitals — for which he received the Legion of Merit. He married Mary Bissell Betts, 'one of the earliest occupational therapists,' and after her 1926 death continued his medical career, practicing internal medicine and cardiology in Pensacola until 1968."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Minister's son; sister led American missions board","body":"Edward Packard came from a distinguished New England clerical family — his father was a D.D. minister and his sister Agnes Cooper served as president of the New York branch of the Women's Board of Missions and held a twenty-year membership on the American Board of Commissioners for Foreign Missions. A niece, Carol Packard Cooper, was among the country's first open heart surgery patients, operated on by Dr. Denton Cooley in 1959 at age seventeen."}],"quotes":[],"sources":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"slug":"edward-packard-jr-1883"},"HD4419":{"id":"HD4419","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":true,"bio":{"first_name":"Mary","middle_na